[
    {
        "content": "<p><code>def Test (\\alpha : Type u) : Type w := sorry</code> specify two universes for Test; how could I do this in a <code>variable</code> declaration?</p>",
        "id": 466103176,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1724961678
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>just <code>variable (\\alpha : Type u)</code>?</p>",
        "id": 466103482,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1724961760
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"684366\">Edward van de Meent</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/How.20do.20I.20specify.20the.20universe.20in.20a.20.60variable.60.20declaration.3F/near/466103482\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>just <code>variable (\\alpha : Type u)</code>?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hm, but say, #check on <code>Test</code> returns <code>Test.{u}</code> while #check on <code>\\alpha</code> does not output something similar to <code>\\alpha.{u}</code>, does this change of notation imply something?</p>",
        "id": 466104103,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1724961939
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>basically: no. what <code>.{u}</code> shows is that <code>Test</code> is a function with a type signature that depends on a universe level, rather than one where the universe levels are constant.</p>",
        "id": 466105783,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1724962592
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"684366\">Edward van de Meent</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/How.20do.20I.20specify.20the.20universe.20in.20a.20.60variable.60.20declaration.3F/near/466105783\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>basically: no. what <code>.{u}</code> shows is that <code>Test</code> is a function with a type signature that depends on a universe level, rather than one where the universe levels are constant.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I see, so the following variable should have the same type as <code>Test</code>, right?</p>\n<p><code>variable (Test2 : Type u -&gt; Type u)</code></p>\n<p>(and thanks a lot for taking the time)</p>",
        "id": 466106908,
        "sender_full_name": "nrs",
        "timestamp": 1724963074
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it's close, but not quite. there is a small difference; it's the difference between \"for all numbers <code>x</code>, <code>P x</code> holds\" and \"let <code>x</code> be a number such that <code>P x</code> holds\"</p>",
        "id": 466107258,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1724963225
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>this <code>Test2</code> is what you get if you were to substitute the universe variable <code>u</code> in <code>Test</code> for a universe level <code>u</code> that is in the local context. in short, it's the same as <code>Test.{u}</code></p>",
        "id": 466107552,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1724963344
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(rather than <code>Test</code>)</p>",
        "id": 466107591,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1724963361
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>you can see this difference in the following example:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">universe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Test</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Test2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">check</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Test</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Test x : Type w</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">check</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Test2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- application type mismatch</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\">/-</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">  Test2 x</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">argument</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">  x</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">has type</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">  Type w : Type (w + 1)</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">but is expected to have type</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">  Type u : Type (u + 1)</span>\n<span class=\"cm\">-/</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 466108459,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1724963677
    },
